\par }\pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid5792777 \f1\fs20\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\f48\insrsid5792777 
These algorithms are variations on a common theme. We match up edges and centers and then simply solve as a 3\'d73\'d73 cube. The seven-step algorithm, and improvement over the 8-step,}{\insrsid5792777 
 is a "cleaner" version of this since all the edges are oriented correctly early by combining the 2nd step with Thistlethwaite step #1. 
\par The steps of the 8-step algorithm can be combined a variety of ways to produce more efficient solutions. One such way i
s illustrated in the 7-step algorithm. We could also take this further and combine step #3 with Thistlethwaite #2 and step #4 with Thistlethwaite #3. Of course, we could also combine the steps in pairs: #1 and #2, #3 and #4, #5 and #6, #7 and #8. The pair
ing up of the Thistlethwaite steps was done by Kociemba. 
\par }{\f48\insrsid5792777 The way that the 4\'d74\'d74 is reduced to the 3\'d73\'d73 has some parallels to the original Thistlethwaite algorithm. For example, after we orient the edges of the 4\'d74\'d74, we restrict turns of the L and R layer}{
\insrsid5792777 
s to half turns (we also restrict the inner layers to half turns). After step 1 of the Thistlethwaite algorithm, we also restrict the L and R layers to half turns. After we pair up edges in step 3, we only allow half turns of the F and B faces (in additio
n to the L and R faces). The Thistlethwaite algorithm does the same thing after its step 2.
